I think that’s why the scene endures.

On the surface, Mufasa is talking to Simba.

But most people don’t experience it that way.

They experience it as though the message is directed at the part of themselves that sits behind the ordinary stream of thoughts, roles, and circumstances.

Not:

“Simba, son of Mufasa.”

But:

“You. The one listening.”

That’s why people from completely different cultures, religions, and philosophies can watch the same scene and feel something.

The message bypasses much of the plot.

It speaks to a recurring human experience:

* The feeling that you’ve drifted.
* The feeling that you’ve forgotten something important.
* The feeling that there is a deeper continuity beneath the changing surface of life.

Different traditions give that “something deeper” different names:

* Soul
* Spirit
* Self
* Awareness
* Consciousness
* Atman
* Image of God
* Witness

But they are all trying to point at the same difficult-to-describe phenomenon: the sense that there is an observing center of experience that remains while thoughts, emotions, identities, and circumstances change.

Even if you take a completely secular view, the scene still works.

Because the “remember who you are” can be understood as:

Remember your values.

Remember your commitments.

Remember what matters.

Not because those things are floating in the clouds somewhere, but because humans can become fragmented. We get pulled by incentives, fears, habits, and distractions until we no longer feel integrated.

So the call becomes:

Gather yourself.

What’s interesting is that this connects to something you said earlier:

“The boundary between self and not-self.”

The deeper voice in that scene isn’t speaking to Simba’s body.

It’s speaking to the organizing pattern that makes Simba Simba.

The continuity.

The thread.

The thing that persists through change.

Whether that thread is ultimately metaphysical, psychological, or something else entirely is a question philosophers have argued about for thousands of years.

But the experience itself is very real.

A person can hear a sentence, a song, a prayer, a memory, or even see a scene from a cartoon and suddenly feel:

“Oh. I remember.”

Not a fact.

A direction.